    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>
                <hi rend="underline">
                    <add>Hebrew</add>
                </hi>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>, <date>4<hi rend="sup"
                        >th</hi> Heshvan, 1850</date></p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <date>(Nov.)</date>
            </p>
            <p>Of the fat of heaven may <sic>handfulls</sic>, blessings<lb/> and life etc. the
                accomplished <persName>Isaac Leeser</persName>,</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Indirectly, through God's friend and mine,<lb/> the learned, wise,
                accomplished <persName>Mister Niumburg</persName><lb/> of the Congregation Kenesseth
                Israel in this city,<lb/> about the great commotion <del>caused</del> between<lb/>
                your honorable self and the rabbi of the cong-<lb/>regation of
                    <placeName>Charleston</placeName>. The basis of the dis-<lb/>pute is the meaning
                of the words "I will<lb/> be what I will be" in the Biblical portion<lb/> of Exodus
                3:14, and I decided that I too<lb/> ought to look into, and apply my limited<lb/>
                mind to the meaning of these words according<lb/> to my small comprehension and in
                so far<lb/> as God grants me the power to do so, and then<lb/> present my results
                before you. Since, how-<lb/>ever my knowledge and worth do not seem to fit<lb/>
                <del>for</del> me for it, and since the meaning of these<lb/> words is very profound
                and it is hard to get<lb/> it through superficial translation, I decided<lb/> to
                support my self <del>own ideas with</del> by the words of our</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>sages, "Sometimes a pearl is found in very<lb/> poor wrappings." And so I begin—</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">First I must point out several difficulties<lb/> in that very verse
                (14)</p>
            <p>1-Why is the words "and he said" used twice in the<lb/> same verse?</p>
            <p>2-Why is the expression, "Thus shalt thou say" used<lb/> after the second "and he
                said"? If this is an<lb/> answer to a question by <persName>Moses</persName>, the
                Torah<lb/> might have said briefly, "And God said<lb/> to
                <persName>Moses</persName>, 'thus shall you say to the Children of<lb/>
                <placeName>Israel</placeName>, I will be that I will be sent me to<lb/> you'"</p>
            <p>3-Why is it <del>said</del> repeated in the following verse, "Thus<lb/> shalt thou
                say to the Children of <placeName>Israel</placeName>," and<lb/> why does God remind
                him in this verse and<lb/> not before that <del>he</del>
                <persName>Moses</persName> is to say to <placeName>Israel</placeName><lb/> "God of
                    <persName>Abraham</persName>, <persName>Isaac</persName>, and
                    <persName>Jacob</persName>?<lb/> Now for the answer—</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The great sight which <persName>Moses</persName> saw in the
                bush<lb/> when God came to him alone, was the first vision<lb/> at that time
                    <persName>Moses</persName> did not know the nature of<lb/> God, nor his Name,
                nor his attributes. That<lb/> is why <persName>Moses</persName> asked the name, i.e.
                "If <placeName>Israel</placeName><lb/> want to know your name by which they
                might</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>know and believe in you that you are their<lb/> redeemer, if they ask me such a
                question<lb/> what shall I tell them?" God's answer them<lb/> was "I will be that I
                will be" i. e. "You<lb/> need not know or announce my name,<lb/> for I need no
                announcement of my name<lb/> except through my deeds. For I am ever-<lb/>lasting,
                and my name is already well<lb/> known in the world. Moreover, they may<lb/> not ask
                you about this. But only if<lb/> by chance they do ask you, say to them<lb/> 'I will
                be sent me to you', i. e. say<lb/> to them, "the Everlasting sent me to you!"<lb/>
                The meaning of the second "I will be" is<lb/> "say to them, 'I will be a father to
                them and<lb/> a redeemer from Pharoah'," And if they<lb/> are not satisfied even
                with this, the second<lb/> "Thus shalt thou say" is used i.e. "Say unto<lb/> them,
                that I shall remain, and realize for<lb/> them that which I promised to
                    <persName>Abraham</persName>,<lb/>
                <persName>Isaac</persName> and <persName>Jacob</persName>, namely to redeem
                them<lb/> and bring them forth with great wealth,<lb/> that I am to be trusted with
                regard to my</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>covenant and my promises for the Ever-<lb/>lasting One of
                    <placeName>Israel</placeName> does not lie or change<lb/> His mind, for He is
                not man to change.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Now I beg of you not be angry at<lb/> me that I have written at such
                length<lb/> and have thus become a burden with my<lb/> lowly writing. But please let
                me know<lb/> whether you liked my idea, then will<lb/> I rejoice very much, in the
                midst of<lb/> my pre-occupation with <del>p</del> general<lb/> affairs and with
                earning a living.<lb/> Your well-wisher</p>
            <p><persName role="author">Simha Hirsch</persName>—?</p>
            <p>
                <add>?</add>
            </p>
            <p>of <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
        </body>
